## Nyasaland Protectorate (Formerly known as British Central Africa)

###1897 One penny surcharge

<div style="width:98%;float:left">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/BCA/SG53.jpg" style="width:98%;float:left" >
<p style="font-size:smaller">
Nyasaland: 1897 1d. on 3s. black and sea green in a mint block of six from the foot of the sheet with plate number, one showing variety 'PNNEY' for 'PENNY' [R. 2/4], fine mint, others slightly heavily mounted, rare. S.G. 53, a, cat. £5,000+. Photo.
£2500...£3000</p>	




</div>

This was a surcharge of __ONE PENNY__ in red on the 3s black and green issue. It produced a number of varieties, one of which is
illustrated above and the rest below.
<hr/>

##Varieties

These are __PNNEY__, __PENN__ and double overprint. Variations of the double overprint exist.
<div style="width:48%;float:left">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/BCA/SG53b.jpg" style="float:left;width:98%" >
Nyasaland: 1897 1d. on 3s. black and sea green, variety 'PENN' ('Y' virtually omitted), cancelled Fort Johnston 'JA 1/99', fine. S.G. 53b, cat. £2,000. Photo.
	

£600...£800
</div>
<div style="width:48%;float:left">
<img src="http://localhost/egypt/BCA/SG53c.jpg" style="float:left;width:98%" >
Nyasaland: 1897 1d. on 3s. black and sea green, variety surcharge double, mint with usual pink backing paper adhesions, fine. S.G. 53c, cat. £500. Photo.
	

£200...£250
</div>

##Covers

Covers are worth a premium, normally in the range of 2-5 normal.

##Blocks

Blocks especially with varieties are worth from 5N.


